The instructor simply uses Google's premade resume and letter templates and fills them out while you watch. Unless you have never encountered a resume before, there is no value in this course.
you only have to edit google docs template. Not much input on how to efectively/intelligently.

this is fine for a high school graduate or someone who never used google docs. otherwise this is common knowledge. also the focus is on the setup not the content, so you will not learn how to WRITE EFFECTIVELY for your resume.

I didn't make it all the way through, because when I saw the example cover letter and resume I felt it had a lot of the things I've been told not to include in them. I won't be completing the course. However, the instructor performed very well.
The "rhyme" software or lab which runs on parallel side of lesson is really really slow and my laptop started to hang or lag too after using this.
Does not teach you how to create a good resume, only a generic resume with a generic format. This project is more about using google docs rather than creating good resumes

It was a well-taught course. The instructor knew what he was talking about. But the course was primarily about how to create a resume and cover letter from a template in Google Docs, which is useful, but I was hoping for more input on what makes a good resume, you know, the content and ways or wording things. But at least with this template that I created during the course, I can maintain a working document to catalogue my skills and be ready with a final document when a job comes along.
This course needs to be extended and various technical writing aspects must also be taught.
Somehow good but we need advanced templates.
